<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-02-26T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-02-26T10:00:00-05:00" n="87" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d87">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94/1972: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Substance]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-02-27T00:00:00+09:00">February 27,
                                    1941—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received February 27—12:10
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>334. Yesterday I told Matsuoka that I entirely concurred in and approved
                            of all that Dooman had said to Ohashi on February 14. As the latter had
                            given only an oral report of the conversation to Matsuoka I read him the
                            whole memorandum of it. I was somewhat surprised when the Minister
                            stated his entire agreement with what Dooman had said. Today I am
                            sending Matsuoka for his personal use a copy of the memorandum.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>